Translations were inaccurate. Both of the stated "literal" translations of both "ab urbe condita" and "anno urbis conditæ" are incorrect translations of the Latin. condita is a passive participle modifying the word city, and both are in the ablative case, making the most literal translation "from the founded city". with anno urbis conditae the same point about it being a particple is true, however now it is in the genitive case, meaning it should be "in the year OF the founded city".
